pullRequest.body:
The bundled hom approach to Freiman homomorphisms is a fail. It is very hard to use and doesn't bring anything. That is because Freiman homs don't have much structure and we do not study them under this angle.

This PR replaces the bundled homs by predicates and moves the file from `Algebra.Group.Freiman` to `Combinatorics.Additive.FreimanHom` so that:
* It is clear these are combinatorial objects, not algebraic ones.
* The diff isn't completely mangled. Nothing was kept so it's not worth comparing via a naïve git diff.

Also fix a few oddities accidentally introduced in #12701.

This just feels like noise at this point: Nobody ever used these in mathlib nor will have an unported project depending on them.

Should I just remove?
I don't care too much. Let's leave them in for now...
The SalemSpencer bits of this file need to be fixed now given recent changes I think.
#12682 hasn't landed yet. I will update whichever PR lands last.
There's an 'if and only if' missing somewhere here (the actual formal definition below is fine).
Again, check all uses of SalemSpencer in this file given recent changes.
I wonder whether `IsFreimanHomOn` wouldn't be a more more mathlib-idiosyncratic name.

I know where you are coming from, but Freiman homs were introduced to create an intrinsic additive theory of sets, namely without references to an ambient group.

I have no use for the intrinsic theory yet (and I'm not sure it will catch on for formalisation), so I am defining the intrinsic theory tools in an extrinsic context (namely for sets in an ambient group). The sets `A` and `B` *are* the spaces, and not `α` and `β`, just as manifolds in R^n *are* the spaces rather than the ambient R^n.

In short, `IsMulFreimanHomOn` is an inappropriate name that does not reflect the mathematical reality. More pragmatically, no one will ever need an "unrestricted" version of `IsMulFreimanHom`.

I don't understand what you mean by that “I know where you are coming from”.

Maybe the thing that makes the definition look awkward in mathlib is that the map f : alpha -> beta only matters through its restriction A to B, but this is standard to have maps defined on the whole type.

I mean that I know most morphisms come from algebra or geometry and are defined on the entire type, so one would expect the same to hold here.

But yeah we agree. It is standard to not use partial maps, and is justified here by the fact that `β` is nonempty (it's a group).

In this story, the role of `B` is different from the role of `A`. In fact, one could imagine stating `IsAddFreimanHom n A` (without any reference to `B`) and adding `MapsTo f A B` when needed. This would be slightly different from what is done in paper math but maybe more natural here.

This is how it was done previously (see `Algebra.Group.Freiman`) and it was painful.

Mathematically, removing `B` is wrong since, as explained above, `A`, `B` are the spaces defined extrinsically through ambient groups `α`, `β`.

Pragmatically, removing `B` is annoying because it makes the composition of Freiman homs not necessarily be a Freiman hom.
The second argument looks legit to me.
